The user updates his self-description as follows: I enjoy synth‑forward, groove‑first records with punchy, roomy analog synths, tactile piano accents, syncopated locked drums and a snappy low end; close‑mic, forward breathy vocals with low reverb that deliver immediacy and presence; concise 3–4 minute dance/new‑wave forms and economical overdubs with low‑compression mastering. I also value tape warmth and alive analog character, restrained mastering that preserves transient snap and headroom, tasteful backing harmonies and clear melodic focus. Vocals should retain breath and consonant detail—whether front‑of‑room natural room or intimate close‑mic—so arrangements let the voice cut through without being masked. Dislikes: heavy compression or loudness‑crush, excessive modern polish or multitracked glue, deadened/overprocessed vocals that lose breath, synths or riffs that swamp the vocal, and long amorphous detours.

You update your description as follows: Groove‑forward funk/rock soundtrack with punchy, transient‑forward drums, syncopated bass and warm tape sheen; room‑front, breathy lead vocals with tactile micro‑dynamics, song‑serving guitar solos and tight backing parts, modest compression and mastering that preserves headroom and lyrical clarity.

